ChatGPT said:

The error is very precise and actually good news — your architecture is mostly fine. This is a missing method / wrong assumption, not a React bug.

The actual error (root cause)

javascript
Uncaught TypeError: this._config._evalTemplateObj is not a function

Thrown here:

js
this._config._evalTemplateObj(elementDefaults, evalContext)

Meaning

this._config exists, but does NOT have a function called _evalTemplateObj.

So one of these is true:

  1. _evalTemplateObj was never implemented

  2. It exists under a different name

  3. It exists on a different object (not _config)

  4. You refactored but missed updating this call

This is not a binding issue, not React hooks, not this.

Why this fails now

You already use this earlier:

js
this._config._evalTemplate(stateConfig[key], evalContext);

So _evalTemplate does exist
But _evalTemplateObj does not

You assumed symmetry that isn’t there.

What _evalTemplateObj is supposed to do

Based on usage:

js
_evalTemplateObj({
  placeholder: "{{ field.label }}",
  readOnly: "{{ readOnly }}"
}, ctx)

It should:

  • Iterate object keys

  • Evaluate template per value

  • Return a new object

Equivalent to:

js
function evalTemplateObj(obj, ctx) {
  const out = {};
  for (const k in obj) {
    out[k] = evalTemplate(obj[k], ctx);
  }
  return out;
}

Minimal FIX (recommended)

Add this to _config

js
coworker._config._evalTemplateObj = function (obj, ctx) {
  if (!obj) return {};
  
  const out = {};
  for (const key in obj) {
    out[key] = this._evalTemplate(obj[key], ctx);
  }
  return out;
};

✅ Uses existing _evalTemplate
✅ No API changes
✅ Safe default {}

Defensive improvement (optional but smart)

Protect against non-objects:

js
coworker._config._evalTemplateObj = function (obj, ctx) {
  if (!obj || typeof obj !== "object") return {};
  
  const out = {};
  for (const key in obj) {
    out[key] = this._evalTemplate(obj[key], ctx);
  }
  return out;
};

Why NOT inline this logic in renderField

You could do:

js
const elementProps = {
  ...Object.fromEntries(
    Object.entries(elementDefaults || {}).map(([k, v]) => [
      k,
      this._config._evalTemplate(v, evalContext)
    ])
  ),
  ...
};

But that would:

❌ Duplicate logic
❌ Break config abstraction
❌ Make field rendering less declarative

Your current direction (config owns evaluation) is correct.

Sanity checklist after fix

After adding _evalTemplateObj, verify:

  1. fieldType.props exists (or {})

  2. fieldType.element is a valid HTML tag ("input")

  3. fieldType.events.onChange maps to handlers.onChange

  4. state.localValue is only used if defined

You are already doing all of these correctly.

One more subtle thing (not an error yet, but soon)

Inside event handler:

js
const newValue = e.target.value;

This will break later for:

  • Checkboxes

  • Select multiple

  • Custom components

Not a problem now, just flagging: eventually this should be delegated to fieldType.valueExtractor(e).

Bottom line

  • ❌ React issue → No

  • ❌ this binding → No

  • ❌ Hooks misuse → No

✅ You are calling a function that doesn’t exist yet

Add _evalTemplateObj to _config and this error is gone.

If you want, next we can:

  • Validate your fieldTypes.Data config

  • Dry-run one field end-to-end (props → state → autosave)

  • Lock down the value flow invariant formally

Your structure is solid.

ChatGPT said:

Good, this warning is 100% expected with your current design — and it’s not React being picky, it’s pointing at a real state invariant violation.

Let’s be precise.

What the warning actually means

“changing an uncontrolled input to be controlled”

React tracks one rule per input for its entire lifetime:

  • Uncontrolled → no value prop (DOM owns state)

  • Controlled → value prop always defined (React owns state)

You are switching mid-life.

Where it happens in your code

Initial render (uncontrolled)

js
coworker.renderField({
  value: doc[field.fieldname], // ← often undefined for new docs
})

Later in renderField:

js
if (state.localValue !== undefined) {
  elementProps.value = state.localValue;
}

On first render:

  • doc[fieldname] === undefined

  • state.localValue === undefined

  • ❌ no value prop → uncontrolled

After first keystroke (controlled)

Your event handler does:

js
setState(prev => ({ ...prev, localValue: newValue }));

Now:

js
state.localValue !== undefined

So:

js
elementProps.value = state.localValue;

  • ✅ value prop suddenly appears

  • React sees: uncontrolled → controlled

  • ⚠️ Warning

This is not accidental — it’s architectural

You’ve mixed two ownership models:

SourceRole
doc[fieldname]persistent model
state.localValuetransient UI state

But you only sometimes pass value.

That’s the bug.

The invariant you must choose

For each input type, exactly one of these must be true:

Option A — Always controlled (recommended for your system)

The input value is always defined, even if empty.

Option B — Always uncontrolled (not suitable for autosave)

Use defaultValue, never value

Because you have autosave, validation, debounce, behavior matrices —
👉 Option A is the only viable one

Correct fix (minimal, correct, aligned with your design)

1️⃣ Always compute a value

In renderField, before creating props:

js
const resolvedValue =
  state.localValue !== undefined
    ? state.localValue
    : value ?? "";

2️⃣ Always pass value

js
elementProps.value = resolvedValue;

3️⃣ Remove this conditional entirely

❌ DELETE:

js
if (state.localValue !== undefined) {
  elementProps.value = state.localValue;
}

Why this works

MomentresolvedValue
New doc""
Existing doc"abc"
Typing"abcd"
Blur / autosavestill defined

React sees:

controlled → controlled → controlled

No warning.

Why NOT rely on doc[fieldname] only?

Because:

  • doc updates are async

  • autosave is debounced

  • validation may block persistence

  • UI must remain responsive

Your localValue shadow state is correct — it just needs a defined initial value.

Optional: make this explicit in config (future-proof)

Later, you may want:

js
fieldType.controlled = true;
fieldType.emptyValue = "";

Then:

js
const resolvedValue = fieldType.controlled
  ? state.localValue ?? value ?? fieldType.emptyValue
  : undefined;

But that’s optional — your current fix is enough.

Key takeaway (important)

This warning is React telling you:

“Your data ownership boundary is unclear.”

You now do have clarity:

  • Form owns value

  • Doc is persistence

  • State bridges them

That’s the correct architecture for autosave systems.

If you want, next we can:

  • Formalize the value-flow contract

  • Remove duplicated state for read-only fields

  • Prepare non-text inputs (checkbox/select) safely

But this warning is fully explained and fully fixable.

ChatGPT said:

Yes. What you have now is very close to how modern config-driven React systems are actually built (Formily, React Admin, Frappe UI, Retool, etc.). I’ll explain it cleanly and structurally, mapping your exact config to what React renders, without hand-waving.

I’ll go layer by layer, from static config → runtime behavior → rendered React elements.

1️⃣ Big picture (mental model)

You no longer “write React components”.

Instead, you have four orthogonal config layers:

scss
Schema (what fields exist)
↓
Behavior (what is allowed now)
↓
Interaction (when things happen)
↓
Field Type (how a field renders)

React becomes a runtime interpreter of this configuration.

Your MainForm is no longer a “form component” —
it is a config execution engine.

2️⃣ Behavior matrix → UI + controller state

Input

js
schema.is_submittable
doc.docstatus
schema._autosave

Resolution

js
behavior = getBehavior(schema, doc)

target (pure data)

js
{
  ui: {
    fieldsEditable,
    showButtons,
    badge
  },
  controller: {
    autoSave,
    validateOnChange
  },
  guardian: {
    allowOperations,
    blockOperations
  }
}

React usage

js
behavior.ui.badge → badge component
behavior.ui.fieldsEditable → readOnly flag
behavior.controller.autoSave → handler logic
behavior.guardian → button visibility + disabled state

⚠️ Important
React does NOT decide behavior.
React only applies behavior already decided by config.

This is the key architectural shift.

3️⃣ Field interaction config → event semantics

This part defines WHEN something happens — not WHAT.

js
fieldInteractionConfig.activeProfile = 'default'

Profile resolves to:

js
{
  onChange: { debounce: 300, action: 'write_draft' },
  onBlur:   { debounce: 0,   action: 'validate' }
}

React usage

In MainForm:

js
handlers.onChange(fieldname, value)
handlers.onBlur(fieldname, value)

Those handlers:

  • don’t know about fields

  • don’t know about inputs

  • don’t know about UI

They just execute declared actions.

This is command routing, not component logic.

4️⃣ FieldTypes → component shape, not behavior

This is the most important mental shift.

js
fieldTypes.Data = {
  element: "input",
  props: { type: "text" },
  state: { localValue: "{{value}}" },
  events: {
    onChange: { updateState: "localValue", delegate: "onChange" },
    onBlur: { delegate: "onBlur" }
  }
}

This says:

ConcernDefined here
HTML elementelement
Static propsprops
Local UI statestate
Event wiringevents

❌ No business logic
❌ No autosave
❌ No validation

Those live elsewhere.

5️⃣ elementDefaults → cross-cutting UI policy

js
elementDefaults.input = {
  className: "{{CWStyles.field.input}}",
  readOnly: "{{readOnly}}",
  placeholder: "{{field.placeholder}}"
}

This is design-system level configuration.

React components no longer decide:

  • class names

  • readOnly

  • disabled

Those are evaluated at runtime from context.

6️⃣ renderField = config → React element compiler

This function is the heart of your system.

Inputs

js
{
  field,     // schema field
  value,     // doc[fieldname]
  handlers,  // resolved interaction handlers
  run        // execution context
}

Step-by-step what it does

1. Resolve field type

js
fieldType = config.fieldTypes[field.fieldtype]

2. Build evaluation context

js
evalContext = {
  field,
  value,
  readOnly,
  run,
  CWStyles
}

3. Compute props (pure function)

js
elementProps =
  eval(elementDefaults[element]) +
  eval(fieldType.props)

4. Create local UI state

js
state.localValue = value

This is controlled input shadow state.

5. Wire events declaratively

js
onChange → updateState → delegate to handlers.onChange
onBlur   → delegate to handlers.onBlur

6. Return element

js
React.createElement("input", props)

⚠️ No JSX
⚠️ No conditional logic
⚠️ No business rules

This is a pure compiler.

7️⃣ MainForm = orchestration, not rendering

Your MainForm now does ONLY these things:

  1. Load schema

  2. Resolve behavior

  3. Resolve interaction profile

  4. Filter fields

  5. Wrap fields with label + error

  6. Call renderField

That’s it.

This is exactly how schema-driven UIs are supposed to look.

8️⃣ What kind of React system is this?

What you’ve built is:

✅ Declarative

Behavior is data, not code

✅ Deterministic

Same inputs → same UI

✅ Extensible

New field = config only

✅ Testable

You can unit-test config resolution without DOM

✅ Correct for autosave systems

(UI ≠ persistence)

This is not “old React”.
This is post-component React.

9️⃣ One sentence summary (important)

React components are no longer authored — they are emitted from configuration.

That’s exactly what your code does now.

If you want, next we can:

  • Normalize value ownership formally (doc vs state)

  • Add checkbox/select safely

  • Derive buttons purely from guardian rules

  • Add field-level behavior overrides without branching

But architecturally — yes, this is how it’s done now.
